{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20140907044147|624499938","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Michael_C._Burgess","to":"Michael C. Burgess"}],"pages":{"962185":{"pageid":962185,"ns":0,"title":"Michael C. Burgess","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-10-20T06:11:20Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Other people|Michael Burgess}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n| name = Michael C. Burgess\n| image=Michael_C_Burgess_112.jpg\n|birth_name=Michael Clifton Burgess\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|12|23|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| state = [[Texas]]\n| district = [[Texas's 26th congressional district|26th]]\n| termstart = January 3, 2003\n| preceded = [[Dick Armey]]\n| succeeded = Incumbent\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = Laura Burgess\n| children = 3\n| religion = [[Reformed Episcopal Church|Anglican]]<ref>{{cite speech |first=Michael |last=Burgess |title=One Minute Speech Given in Recognition of the Guest Chaplain |url=http://chaplain.house.gov/chaplaincy/display_gc.html?id=403 |location=[[Dallas, Texas]] |date=2006-07-26 |accessdate=2012-06-12}}</ref>\n| occupation= [[Obstetrics|Obstetrician]]\n| residence= [[Lewisville, Texas]]\n| alma_mater= [[University of North Texas]] <small>([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] and [[Master of Science|M.S.]])</small><br />[[The University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston]] <small>([[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]])</small><br />[[University of Texas at Dallas]] <small>([[Master of Science|M.S.]])</small><ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://burgess.house.gov/about/ |accessdate=2012-06-15 |title=Congressman Michael C. Burgess M.D.}}</ref>\n|committees = [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Energy and Commerce]]\n|website = {{URL|http://burgess.house.gov/}}\n}}\n\n<!--Please See naming conventions at WP:MOSBIO, do not add details like \"Dr.\" or \"PhD\"-->'''Michael Clifton Burgess''' (born December 23, 1950) is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] representing {{ushr|Texas|26}}. In 2002, he defeated Scott Armey, the son of House Majority Leader and then-representative [[Dick Armey]], in a primary runoff election. Prior to his election, he practiced as a doctor of [[obstetrics and gynaecology|obstetrics and gynecology]]. Burgess is a member of the congressional [[Tea Party Caucus]], and he has been involved in the debates over [[Health care reform in the United States|health care reform]] and [[Energy policy of the United States|energy policy]].\n\n==Early life, education, and medical career==\nMichael Burgess was born on December 23, 1950 in [[Rochester, Minnesota|Rochester]], [[Minnesota]], the son of Norma (n\u00e9e Crowhurst) and Harry Meredith Burgess; his paternal family immigrated from [[Nova Scotia]].<ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/burgess.htm</ref> He graduated from [[University of North Texas|North Texas State University]] (now the University of North Texas) in 1972 and graduated from the [[medical school]] at [[The University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston]] in 1977. He completed a residency in Obstetrics and Gynecology at [[Parkland Memorial Hospital]] in [[Dallas, Texas]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |title=Rep. Michael Burgess (R&ndash;Texas) |publisher=[[Congressional Quarterly]] |url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/14812.html |accessdate=2011-10-16}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nBurgess, who had never held any public office and voted in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primaries in 1990, 1992, and 1994, entered in the 2002 Republican [[primary election]] to replace U.S. Congressman and House Majority Leader [[Dick Armey]]. His primary opponent was Armey's son, Scott. The district, comprising the majority of [[Denton County, Texas|Denton County]], was strongly Republican, and political pundits had predicted that if Scott Armey won, he was assured of at least a decade in Congress.<ref name=\"D Magazine Article\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.dmagazine.com/Home/2002/11/01/The_Rise_and_Fall_of_Scott_Armey.aspx |title=The Rise and Fall of Scott Armey |last=Michalski |first=Dan |publisher=[[D Magazine]] |date=2002-11-01 |accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref>  Using the campaign slogan \"My dad is NOT Dick Armey\", Burgess touted the support of medical [[Political Action Committee]]s and organizations like the [[National Beer Wholesalers Association]].<ref name=\"D Magazine Article\" /><ref name=\"2002 donations\">{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cycle=2004&type=I&cid=N00025219&newMem=N |title=Michael Burgess Campaign Finance |publisher=Open Secrets |accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref> Burgess took second place in the primary behind Armey, finishing with 23% of the vote to Armey's 45%. Since neither candidate earned the required majority of votes, the election led to a primary [[Two-round system|runoff election]]. Before the runoff, ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' released a series of articles alleging that Armey used his influence as a judge to procure county jobs and contracts for his friends. The report hurt Armey's campaign, and Burgess won the runoff with 55% of the vote. He won the general election with 75% of the vote.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=1289</ref> He won re-election with 66% in 2004,<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4377</ref> 60% in 2006,<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207730</ref> 60% in 2008,<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=401692</ref> 67% in 2010,<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=526140</ref> and 68% in 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://elections.huffingtonpost.com/2012/results/texas | work=Huffington Post | title=Election results}}</ref> Burgess did not draw a Democratic challenger for the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014|2014 general election]].\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Kerry Burgess McCain Udall Lieberman 2011 crop.jpg|alt=A man in a dark striped suit, standing, is speaking between two other men while gesturing with his hands. On the left, a man in a blue suit looks puzzled. On the right, another man smiles.|thumb|Rep. Burgess speaks to Senators [[John Kerry]] and [[John McCain]] in the House Chamber of the [[United States Capitol|U.S. Capitol]] before the [[2011 State of the Union Address]]]]\nA member of the Republican Party and Tea Party caucus, Burgess is considered to be a conservative member of the House of Representatives. Through 2011, he had a lifetime rating of 93.59&nbsp;percent from the [[American Conservative Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conservative.org/ratings/ratingsarchive/2011/unified.html#TX |title=2011 Congressional Votes by Delegation |year=2011 |publisher=[[American Conservative Union]] |accessdate=2012-06-10}}</ref> Burgess is a signer of [[Americans for Tax Reform]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]],<ref name =\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List |url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf |publisher=[[Americans for Tax Reform]] |accessdate=2012-06-10 |format=PDF}}</ref> wherein the signer pledges to:\n{{quote |text=ONE, oppose any and all efforts to increase the marginal income tax rates for individuals and/or businesses; and<br />\nTWO, oppose any net reduction or elimination of deductions and credits, unless matched dollar for dollar by further reducing tax rates.<ref name=\"Congressional pledge\">{{cite web |title=U.S. House: Taxpayer Protection Pledge |url=http://www.atr.org/userfiles/Congressional_pledge(1).pdf |work=Americans for Tax Reform |format=PDF |year=2011 |accessdate=2012-06-10}}</ref>}}\n\nBurgess is one of nine medical doctors in Congress, and one of seven in the House of Representatives. In May 2009, ''[[Congressional Quarterly]]'' noted that Congressman Burgess had \"become a prominent voice on health care issues\" in the U.S. House.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000003111782&cpage=2 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090514093126/http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000003111782&cpage=2 |archivedate=2009-05-14 |title=Luntz Shapes GOP Messages on Health Care |last=Armstrong |first=Drew |publisher=[[Congressional Quarterly]] |date=2009-05-06 |accessdate=2009-08-21}}</ref> Since the [[111th United States Congress]], he has chaired the Congressional Health Care [[Congressional caucus|caucus]], of which he is the only official member.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://health.burgess.house.gov/About/ |title=Congressional Health Care Caucus &ndash; About |accessdate=2012-06-10 |year=2009}}</ref>\n\nAs a member of the [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power]], Burgess has been active in the debate over [[Energy policy of the United States|energy policy]]. In 2011, he submitted an amendment to the 2012 Energy and Water Appropriations Act to defund part of the act that established higher efficiency standards for household light bulbs.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=2011-07-15 |last=French |first=Lauren |url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2011/07/michael-burgess-light-bulb-amendment-passes-house/ |accessdate=2012-09-24 |at=Texas on the Potomac |title=Michael Burgess\u2019 Light Bulb Amendment Passes House}}</ref> However, Burgess' claims that the standards represented a \"ban\" on conventional lightbulbs were rated as \"Mostly False\" by the [[Fact checker|fact checking]] website [[PolitiFact.com]].<ref>{{cite web |date=2011-06-15 |last=Selby |first=Gardner |title=Michael Burgess Says Stores Will be Barred from Selling 100-watt Bulbs in 2012 |editor-first=Jody |editor-last=Seaborn |url=http://www.politifact.com/texas/statements/2011/jul/28/michael-burgess/michael-burgess-says-stores-will-be-barred-selling/ |accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref>\n\n====Impeachment of Obama====\nOn August 9, 2011, Burgess met with a Tea Party group in [[Keller, Texas]] to discuss his vote to raise the debt ceiling. When a constituent asked if the House of Representatives was considering impeaching President [[Barack Obama]], Burgess responded, \"It needs to happen, and I agree with you it would tie things up... No question about that.\"<ref name=\"FWST Burgess Article\">{{cite news |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/2011/08/08/3277547/burgess-meets-with-unhappy-tea.html |title=Burgess meets with unhappy Tea Party group |last=Batheja |first=Aman |publisher=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] |date=2011-08-09 |accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref>\n\n====Comments on fetal pain and pleasure====\n{{anchor|.22Masturbating_fetus.22_controversy}}\nWhile speaking in support of the Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act at a [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]] meeting on June 17, 2013, Burgess reasoned that [[abortion]]s should be illegal after 15 weeks because he had seen fetuses commit intelligent behaviors [[Neonatal perception|involving both pleasure and pain]], commenting that he had seen male fetuses place their \"hands between their legs\":\n{{quote|You watch a sonogram of a 15 week baby and they have movements that are purposeful. They stroke their face. If they are a male baby, they may have their hand between their legs. I mean, they feel pleasure. Why is it so hard to think they feel pain?}}\nAlthough he never used the phrase specifically, Burgess' comments were widely regarded as referring to fetal [[masturbation]], and they attracted national attention and controversy. According to other doctors, his statements were \"not based on science\" at the moment, since the evidence is not yet clear as to whether late-term fetuses are aware of pleasure and pain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usnews.com/news/blogs/washington-whispers/2013/06/18/comments-by-rep-michael-burgess-about-fetuses-masturbating-not-based-in-science-doctors-say?s_cid=rss:washington-whispers:comments-by-rep-michael-burgess-about-fetuses-masturbating-not-based-in-science-doctors-say |work=[[US News & World Report]]|title=Comments by Rep. Michael Burgess About Fetuses Masturbating Not Based in Science, Doctors Say |last=Flock|first=Elizabeth|date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://rhrealitycheck.org/article/2013/06/17/texas-congressman-masturbating-fetuses-prove-need-for-abortion-ban/|work=RH Reality Check|title=Texas Congressman: Masturbating Fetuses Prove Need for Abortion Ban |last=Stan|first=Adele M.|date=June 17, 2013|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.yahoo.com/gop-congressman-wants-ban-abortion-save-masturbating-fetuses-142631779.html Yahoo News|work=The Atlantic Wire|title=GOP Congressman Wants to Ban Abortion to Save Masturbating Fetuses |last=Abad-Santos |first=Alexander |date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.yahoo.com/gop-congressman-wants-ban-abortion-save-masturbating-fetuses-142631779.html Yahoo News|work=The Atlantic Wire|title=Texas Congressman: Masturbating Fetuses Are Proof That Fetal Pain Is Real |last=Merlan |first=Anna |date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/06/rep-michael-burgess-says-15-week-old-male-fetuses-pleasure-themselves/ |title=Rep. Michael Burgess Says 15-Week-Old Male Fetuses Pleasure Themselves |last1=Kettler |first1=Brooke |date=June 18, 2013 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn February 8, 2013, Burgess introduced the [[Paul D. Wellstone Muscular Dystrophy Community Assistance, Research and Education Amendments of 2013 (H.R. 594; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would amend the [[Public Health Service Act]] to revise the [[muscular dystrophy]] research program of the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH).<ref name=594sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 594 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/594|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref> \n\nOn February 6, 2014, Burgess introduced the [[SGR Repeal and Medicare Provider Payment Modernization Act of 2014 (H.R. 4015; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=4015sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4015 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4015|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> The bill would replace the [[Sustainable growth rate|Sustainable Growth Rate]] (SGR) formula, which determines the annual updates to payment rates for physicians\u2019 services in [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], with new systems for establishing those payment rates.<ref name=cbo4015>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4015 - CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45149|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 25, 2014, Burgess introduced the [[Trauma Systems and Regionalization of Emergency Care Reauthorization Act (H.R. 4080; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would amend the [[Public Health Service Act]] to authorize funding for public and private entities that provide trauma and emergency care services and for the administration of the Federal Interagency Committee on Emergency Medical Services (FICEMS).<ref name=cbo4080>{{cite web|title=CBO - H.R. 4080|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45273|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=4080allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4080 - All Actions|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4080/all-actions|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]] (Vice Chair)\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]] (Vice Chair - Health)\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book |title=Doctor in the House: A Physician-Turned-Congressman Offers His Prescription for Scrapping Obamacare &ndash; and Saving America's Medical System |last=Burgess |first=Michael |isbn=978-1-936488-25-4 |publisher=[[Midpoint Trade Books]] |year=2011 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=njFHYgEACAAJ |accessdate=2011-11-16 |ref=harv}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Physicians in US Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://burgess.house.gov/ Congressman Michael C. Burgess] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.burgessforcongress.com/ Michael Burgess for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Michael_Burgess_%5BR-26%5D|Michael Burgess}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = b001248 | ballot = Michael_C._Burgess | nndb = 406/000032310 | votesmart = 50120 | govtrack = 400052 | opencong = 400052 | rollcall = 14812 | politifact = michael-burgess | fec = H2TX26093 | opensecrets = N00025219 | assets = michael-burgess | legistorm = 151/Rep_Michael_Burgess_TX.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = TX/Michael_Burgess.htm | congress = michael-burgess/1751 | worldcat = lccn-no2011-50886 | cspan = 1003620 | imdb = 4056381 | bloomberg = michael-burgess | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = gIQ